  "excerpt": "Having made it through the siege of Minas Tirith… more through broken game mechanics than any actual skill… I went from the cleanup within the city out onto the Pelennor, the fields out…",
  "siteName": "The Ancient Gaming Noob",
  "favicon": "",
  "text": "Having made it through the siege of Minas Tirith… more through broken game mechanics than any actual skill… I went from the cleanup within the city out onto the Pelennor, the fields outside the city, between the city walls and the outer wall and Osgiliath, to the camp where Aragorn and the other major players were setting up for the next act. Aragorn’s pavilion on the Pelennor You can see Legolas and Gimli, members of the fellowship, being made to wait outside.  I was allowed in, but only to prove the rather very important yet not important at all state of my part in the proceedings. I got to speak with many important people… so they could assign me menial tasks.  I am starting to see myself as more of a “fixer” in the grand scheme of things, somebody needed to get things done but not somebody you mention in the official history. Mostly I had to run around the Pelennor and account for the missing… which was a sizable list and many of whom were bit players in past scenes, the thane of some little outpost or the captain of this watch or that location.  I mean, I also had to kill some guys, find some lost knickknacks, clean up a few messes, and do the usual message delivery… but I also had the task of roll call of cast whose characters didn’t make it onto the movie poster. And so I rode about, collecting toe tags of the dead. Grimbold dead on the field He made it out of Helm’s Deep only to die here.  But then a lot of people died here. I found Ingold, the captain at the north gate of the outer wall before the siege.  I had to clear away some stray orcs, but he was otherwise still upright and fighting. Ingold, still scrapping However Turgon, who had charge of the south gate of the outer wall before the siege fell in the fight. He left orcs dead around him Then there was Forlong the Fat… seriously, I looked that name up to be sure… who I also remembered, but mostly for standing around during the siege pointing at burning projectiles while I hauled water to put them out. The “Not For Long” joke never gets old Judging from his posture I think he just has a tummy ache.  Probably been picking at the supply wagon again.  He might have died of food poisoning later.  I could swear I saw him on the list of the remembered later on. On checking everybody off the list, I was invited to an instanced memorial where I was asked to light the funeral pyre… I guess being the only person with agency means I have to do everything… as we remembered those who had fallen. The cyno is lit capsuleer Then each of the leaders went down their list of fallen.  I was a bit surprised when Aragorn spoke, because Halbarad was mentioned as one of the fallen. Halbarad gone for the tale I cannot remember if he ever got to hear how I stuck it to the Falcon Clan leader in the caves at Helm’s Deep.  Some others of the Grey Company perished as well, but Halbarad was Aragorn’s main Lieutenant. Then, I went with Eomer to pay respects to Theodan, who  was lying in state within the city. Eomer stating the obvious After which it was time for the big planning session, the “what do we do now?” part of the siege, where they acknowledge that Sauron was just going to come at them again and that the only real hope was the destruction of the ring.  As such, they would set out to the black gate with such forces as they could muster to distract Sauron, to make him think that the new master of the ring sought to assail him, to keep Frodo and Sam’s mission from his mind. Let’s not forget we’re going into a trap as well That included a lot of dialog lifted straight from the book… which is fine.  It is worthwhile to put quotes into the mouths of people who said them. And then I was given another list of tasks, a shopping list of supplies and some recruiting and persuasion objectives as the leaders stood around outside the pavilion and smoked and exchanged anecdotes about past times in the city.  Even Gandalf grew bored with that and stood apart from the military leadership wing of the party. Eomer, Aragorn, Tistann, and Imrahil I will say that Aragorn has a pretty fancy bed in that tent.  Did they grab that out of the city or did some poor contingent of the Grey Company have to carry that broken down into pieces all across Middle-earth? Aragorn’s sleeping chambers I mean, granted, it doesn’t look like he’s slept in it… or used the bath… or read the books on the table… or partook of the smorgasbord of food behind me in that picture… but still, seems pretty sumptuous.  I should be thankful my quest chain didn’t include heating the water for that tub. Anyway, on finally wrapping all of that up, I was sent forward to Osgiliath, the next stop on the journey forward to Mordor. Riding across the Pelennor to Osgiliath Finally the destination of the NPCs aligns with my own destination, which is Mordor.  Over the river and through the woods, to Sauron’s house we go.  There are just a few details to take care of along the way… there always are.",
